<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Spartina</i> <i>alterniflora</i>, <i>Spartina</i> <i>densiflora</i> or another non-native cordgrass is dominant in the herbaceous layer. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Herbs < 1.5 m; cover is continuous. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Spartina densiflora</i> > 50% relative cover in the herbaceous layer (Pickart 2006).</li>
		
		<li><i>Spartina foliosa</i> > 50% relative cover on mudflats, banks, berms, and margins of bays and deltas (Buck-Diaz et al. 2021).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Coastal salt marshes on mudflats, banks, berms, margins of bays, and diked marshes. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (1996 national list) recognizes <i>Spartina alterniflora</i> and <i>S. densiflora</i> as OBL plants. </div>
</div>

        
