<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> DiTomaso and Healy (2007) consider four of the six cordgrass species that occur in California to be non-native. These are perennials that grow to 2.5 m in height. Their leaves have flat or inrolled blades, and their inflorescences are open to dense and narrow. Some plants have fleshy to wiry rhizomes. Water and tides disperse their short-lived seeds and rhizome fragments. Seeds germinate in a few months in lighted substrates (DiTomaso and Healy 2007). See also the <i>Spartina foliosa </i>alliance description. Grewell et al. (2007) have provided a description of the state’s coastal salt marshes, including the importance of these grasses. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Spartina alterniflora, </i>smooth cordgrass, has a Cal-IPC rank of High. It grows to 2.5 m in height with flat leaves and open inflorescences. The rhizomes are large and fleshy. It was unintentionally planted in San Francisco Bay in the 1970s; currently, <i>S. alterniflora </i>x <i>S. foliosa </i>hybrids form an important aspect of the bay’s marshes. Compared to the native <i>S. foliosa, </i>it grows higher in the salt marshes and at higher water levels, invading mudflats and changing the species composition of the upper marshes. Since the two species hybridize, introgression may eventually eliminate <i>S. foliosa</i>. This introduction is native to the Atlantic coast of the United States (DiTomaso and Healy 2007). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Spartina densiflora, </i>Chilean cordgrass, has a Cal-IPC rank of High. It grows to 1.5 m in height with inrolled leaf blades and dense, narrow inflorescences. The rhizomes are mostly lacking. Once considered a northern, tussock form of the native <i>S. foliosa, </i>botanists now regard it an introduction from ship ballasts in the mid-1880s (Faber 2000, Spicher and Josselyn 1985). Plants are locally common in San Francisco Bay and extensive in Humboldt Bay. <i>S. densiflora </i>is native to Argentina and Chile (DiTomaso and Healy 2007). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Spartina anglica, </i>common cordgrass, has a Cal-IPC rank of Moderate. It is an amphidiploid derived from hybridization of <i>S. alterniflora </i>and <i>S. maritima</i>. It developed in Britain after the introduction of <i>S. alterniflora </i>in the 1880s. It grows to 1.3 m in height, with flat leaf blades and slightly open inflorescences. The rhizomes are lacking or wiry. Stands occur in northern San Francisco Bay (DiTomaso and Healy 2007). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Spartina patens, </i>salt-meadow cordgrass, has a Cal-IPC rank of Limited. It grows to 1.2 m in height with inrolled leaf blades and open inflorescences. The rhizomes are lacking or wiry. Stands occur in salt marshes from Sonoma to Santa Barbara Co. (Grewell et al. 2007). It is native to southeastern United States (DiTomaso and Healy 2007). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
