    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Ab). Stands of all four invasive <i>Spartina </i>species threaten <i>S. foliosa </i>and other salt marsh natives in San Francisco Bay and other coastal marshes in the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Aa-m). Stands of <i>S. densiflora </i>are the most extensive salt marsh type around Humboldt Bay (Barnhart et al. 1992, Eicher 1987, Eicher and Sawyer 1989, Grewell et al. 2007). <i>S. anglica </i>is also reported from Humboldt Bay, and <i>S. alterniflora </i>was effectively eliminated in 1996 (Faber 2000). <i>S.  densiflora </i>also occurs in former tidal channels and other areas that receive saltwater inputs from leaking tide gates. It is relatively rare in these saline, diked marshes, and eradication is still quite feasible (Pickart 2006).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> These cordgrasses have changed the species composition of several major coastal salt marsh areas by reducing natives and altering historic vegetation and biological processes (Grewell et al. 2007). The Invasive Spartina Project (http://www.spartina.org/) is a coordinated regional effort among local, state, and federal organizations to eliminate introduced species of <i>Spartina</i>. The project offers a plant field guide, a best practices guide, and the annual Pesticide Application Plan on its website. </div>
</div>

    

    

